7.1.1 - W11SR13: Bypassing Secure Internet Gateway (SIG) Controls
ISM controls:
•	0206; 0209 (Relating to the use of an approved Secure Internet Gateway).
•	0464; 0466 (Relating to the use of Virtual Private Networks (VPNs) to secure communications).
•	0953; 1081 (Relating to web content filtering and SSL/TLS inspection).
•	1182 (Relating to the use of intrusion detection and prevention systems).
Current Risk There is a risk that the lack of a mandatory agency VPN to the Secure Internet Gateway (SIG) for stand-alone workstations will allow these devices to access the internet directly. By bypassing the agency's primary IPS, web, and content filtering controls, the attack surface is significantly increased. This reduced visibility and lack of centralised security control may lead to a compromise of the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of the agency’s system and its sensitive data.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Implement "Always-On" VPN: Deploy an "Always-On" VPN solution (such as Microsoft Tunnel or a third-party equivalent) that forces all internet-bound traffic from stand-alone workstations through the agency SIG.
•	Enforce Endpoint-Based Web Filtering: Implement client-side web content filtering (e.g., Microsoft Defender for Endpoint web protection) to provide a secondary layer of security for when the device is not connected to the corporate network.
•	Disable Split Tunnelling: Configure VPN profiles to strictly prohibit split tunnelling, ensuring that no traffic can bypass the inspection capabilities of the Secure Internet Gateway.
- Treatment #1
•	Utilise Microsoft Intune to deploy and manage persistent VPN profiles that are required for any network connectivity on Windows 11 endpoints.
•	Implement strict firewall rules on the local workstation image to block all outbound traffic except for established VPN tunnels to the SIG.
•	Integrate endpoint telemetry with the agency SIEM to monitor for any attempted or successful network connections that bypass the approved gateway.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented. The enforcement of a mandatory VPN ensures that all workstation traffic remains subject to the agency's robust gateway security controls, including IPS and content filtering. While the consequence of a data breach remains "Moderate," the likelihood of an successful exploit via direct internet access is reduced to "Unlikely" through the elimination of unencrypted or unmonitored egress paths.
